flowRoot.flowPara: Sequestering CO2 emissions on scale requires that humans assume control of major biogeochemical processes. NETs deployment levels estimated in IAMs are approximately equivalent to the entire natural land CO2 sink in 2050, and almost double it in 2100. Although sink and source trends clearly show an emerging (unintentional) "anthropocene" since the 1950s, it may be hubristic to assume that we can actively manage the global carbon cycle, while avoiding the worst side-effects associated with NETs.

NETs allow carbon budgets to expand, inadvertently dis-incentivising costly near-term mitigation. In a set of equivalent scenarios for meeting 2oC, the moral hazard mitigation gap between no-CCS runs versus full-tech runs is as high as 9.1 GtCO2 in 2030. This commits future generations to even steeper emissions reductions in the mid-century and locks-in a long-term dependence on NETs.

Key to the moral hazard criticism is doubt over the social, technical and economic feasibility of upscaling NETs. Few NETs options are currently in operation, only one BECCS plant is functional, while DAC is still in the prototype stage. From this low baseline, annual growth rates of 6-8% would need to be sustained by the mid-century to meet ambitious climate goals.
